The Complete Guide to Real-Time Web Communication for Engineers
Modern web applications demand real-time data delivery. Chat messages, notifications, stock prices, live dashboards, collaborative cursors, AI token streaming — users expect data to arrive the moment it exists, not the next time they refresh the page.
Four approaches dominate this space: short polling, long polling, Server-Sent Events (SSE), and WebSockets. Each solves the same fundamental problem — getting data from server to client quickly — but with radically different trade-offs in latency, complexity, scalability, and infrastructure requirements.
This guide goes beyond surface-level comparisons. We’ll look at how each approach works under the hood, examine production-grade code, discuss the edge cases that break systems at scale, and help you make the right choice for your specific use case.
The decision ultimately comes down to one question: does the client mostly ask for updates, or does the server need to push updates continuously?
TL;DR — If You’re in a Hurry

• Short polling: Client asks “anything new?” every N seconds. Simple but wasteful — 90% of responses are empty. Use for low-stakes dashboards.

• Long polling: Client asks, server waits until data exists before responding. Near-real-time over plain HTTP. Use when SSE/WebSocket aren’t feasible.

• SSE (Server-Sent Events): Server pushes events over a single HTTP connection. Built-in reconnection and resumability. Use for live feeds, notifications, AI streaming. This is the most underused option — try it before reaching for WebSockets.

• WebSockets: Full-duplex, bidirectional. Both sides talk whenever they want. Use for chat, games, collaborative editing — anything truly interactive.
The rule of thumb: polling for simplicity, SSE for server push, WebSockets for bidirectional interaction.

1. Short Polling — The Simplest (and Most Wasteful) Approach
Short polling is the brute-force solution. The client sends an HTTP request to the server at a fixed interval — every 5 seconds, every 30 seconds — regardless of whether anything changed. The server responds immediately with either new data or an empty “nothing to report.”
Think of it like repeatedly calling a restaurant to ask, “Is my table ready?” every two minutes. Simple, but you’re burning phone calls and the host’s patience.
How It Works
Client → Server: "Any updates?" (t=0s)
Server → Client: "No." (immediate)
Client → Server: "Any updates?" (t=5s)
Server → Client: "No." (immediate)
Client → Server: "Any updates?" (t=10s)
Server → Client: "Yes! Here's the data" (immediate)Implementation
Client (JavaScript):
class ShortPoller {
constructor(url, intervalMs = 5000) {
this.url = url;
this.intervalMs = intervalMs;
this.timerId = null;
this.isRequestInFlight = false; // Guard against overlap
} start(onData) {
this.timerId = setInterval(async () => {
// Prevent overlapping requests if previous one is still pending
if (this.isRequestInFlight) return; this.isRequestInFlight = true;
try {
const response = await fetch(this.url);
const data = await response.json();
if (data.hasUpdates) {
onData(data.payload);
}
} catch (error) {
console.error('Poll failed:', error);
// Don't crash — next interval will retry
} finally {
this.isRequestInFlight = false;
}
}, this.intervalMs);
} stop() {
clearInterval(this.timerId);
}
}// Usage
const poller = new ShortPoller('/api/notifications', 10000);
poller.start((data) => {
console.log('New notifications:', data);
});Server (Node.js / Express):
app.get('/api/notifications', async (req, res) => {
const userId = req.user.id;
const lastChecked = req.query.since; // Timestamp of last successful poll const notifications = await db.getNotifications(userId, {
createdAfter: lastChecked,
}); res.json({
hasUpdates: notifications.length > 0,
payload: notifications,
timestamp: Date.now(), // Client sends this back as 'since' next time
});
});Server (Java / Spring Boot):
@RestController
public class NotificationController { @Autowired
private NotificationService notificationService; @GetMapping("/api/notifications")
public ResponseEntity<PollResponse> poll(
@RequestParam("since") long since,
@AuthenticationPrincipal User user) { List<Notification> notifications =
notificationService.getAfter(user.getId(), Instant.ofEpochMilli(since)); return ResponseEntity.ok(new PollResponse(
!notifications.isEmpty(),
notifications,
System.currentTimeMillis()
));
}
}When Short Polling Works

• Admin dashboards refreshing every 30 seconds where exact freshness doesn’t matter

• Simple status checks: “Is my report generated yet?”

• Internal tools with low traffic where efficiency isn’t critical

• Legacy systems where adding persistent connections isn’t feasible

• Situations where your infrastructure team vetoes anything more complex
Edge Cases That Bite in Production
Thundering herd. If 10,000 clients all start polling at the same moment (server restart, page load after a deploy), they’ll synchronize on the interval and hit the server in spikes every N seconds. Fix: add random jitter to the interval.
// Bad: every client polls at exactly 5000ms
setInterval(poll, 5000);// Good: each client polls at 5000ms ± random offset
const jitter = Math.random() * 2000; // 0-2 seconds of randomness
setInterval(poll, 5000 + jitter);Interval overlap. If your server takes 6 seconds to respond but the client polls every 5 seconds, a new request fires before the previous one completes. Requests pile up. Guard with an isRequestInFlight flag as shown in the code above.
Mobile battery drain. Each HTTP request wakes the phone’s radio, which takes significant power. Aggressive polling (every 2–3 seconds) can visibly impact battery life. On mobile, consider increasing the interval to 30–60 seconds or switching to a push-based approach entirely.
Stale data illusion. If real updates happen every second but you poll every 30 seconds, users see data that’s always 15 seconds stale on average. This creates an uncomfortable experience for anything time-sensitive.

2. Long Polling — The Server Holds the Line
Long polling is the clever evolution of short polling. Instead of the server responding immediately with “nothing,” it holds the connection open until there actually IS something to report — or until a timeout expires. The moment the client receives a response, it immediately sends a new request, creating a near-real-time pipeline using ordinary HTTP.
This is like calling the restaurant and the host says, “Hold on, I’ll keep you on the line until your table is ready.” Much more efficient than calling back every two minutes.
How It Works
Client → Server: "Any updates?" (t=0s)
Server: *holds connection open* (waiting...)
Server: *still waiting...* (t=15s)
Server: *data arrives!* (t=23s)
Server → Client: "Yes! Here's the data"
Client → Server: "Any updates?" (immediately reconnects)
Server: *holds connection open* (waiting again...)Implementation
Client (JavaScript):
class LongPoller {
constructor(url) {
this.url = url;
this.isRunning = false;
this.lastEventId = null; // Track last received event for resumability
}async start(onData) {
this.isRunning = true;
while (this.isRunning) {
try {
const params = new URLSearchParams();
if (this.lastEventId) {
params.set('lastEventId', this.lastEventId);
}
const controller = new AbortController();
const timeoutId = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), 65000); // Client-side timeout
const response = await fetch(`${this.url}?${params}`, {
signal: controller.signal,
});
clearTimeout(timeoutId);
if (!response.ok) {
throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);
}
const data = await response.json();
if (data.events && data.events.length > 0) {
this.lastEventId = data.lastEventId;
onData(data.events);
}
// Immediately reconnect - no delay on success
} catch (error) {
if (!this.isRunning) break; // Intentional stop
console.error('Long poll error:', error.message);
// Backoff on errors to avoid hammering a sick server
await this.backoff();
}
}
}
async backoff() {
// Exponential backoff: 1s, 2s, 4s, 8s, max 30s
const delay = Math.min(1000 * Math.pow(2, this.errorCount || 0), 30000);
this.errorCount = (this.errorCount || 0) + 1;
await new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, delay));
}
stop() {
this.isRunning = false;
}
}
// Usage
const poller = new LongPoller('/api/events');
poller.start((events) => {
events.forEach((event) => renderNotification(event));
});
Server (Node.js / Express) — This Is Where the Magic Happens:
// Map of userId → response object (the "parked" connections)
const waitingClients = new Map();app.get('/api/events', (req, res) => {
const userId = req.user.id;
const lastEventId = req.query.lastEventId;
// Check if there's already data waiting (events since last poll)
const pendingEvents = eventStore.getAfter(userId, lastEventId);
if (pendingEvents.length > 0) {
// Data already available - respond immediately
return res.json({
events: pendingEvents,
lastEventId: pendingEvents[pendingEvents.length - 1].id,
});
}
// No data yet - HOLD the connection open
// Store the response object - we'll use it later when data arrives
waitingClients.set(userId, {
res,
lastEventId,
connectedAt: Date.now(),
});
// Timeout: if no data arrives in 55 seconds, respond with empty
// (55s, not 60s - stay under load balancer/proxy timeouts)
const timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
if (waitingClients.has(userId)) {
waitingClients.delete(userId);
res.json({ events: [], lastEventId });
}
}, 55000);
// Cleanup if client disconnects before we respond
req.on('close', () => {
clearTimeout(timeoutId);
waitingClients.delete(userId);
});
});
// This function is called whenever new data arrives for a user
// (from Kafka consumer, database trigger, another API call, etc.)
function deliverEvent(userId, event) {
const client = waitingClients.get(userId);
if (client) {
waitingClients.delete(userId);
client.res.json({
events: [event],
lastEventId: event.id,
});
// Client will immediately reconnect with a new long poll
}
}
Server (Java / Spring Boot):
@RestController
public class LongPollController {
// Thread-safe map of waiting clients
private final ConcurrentHashMap<String, DeferredResult<ResponseEntity<?>>>
waitingClients = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
@GetMapping("/api/events")
public DeferredResult<ResponseEntity<?>> poll(
@RequestParam(required = false) String lastEventId,
@AuthenticationPrincipal User user) {
// DeferredResult tells Spring: "Don't respond yet. I'll set the result later."
// Spring releases the thread but keeps the TCP connection open.
DeferredResult<ResponseEntity<?>> result = new DeferredResult<>(55000L);
// Check for immediately available data
List<Event> pending = eventStore.getAfter(user.getId(), lastEventId);
if (!pending.isEmpty()) {
result.setResult(ResponseEntity.ok(new EventResponse(pending)));
return result;
}
// Park the request - store it for later
waitingClients.put(user.getId(), result);
// Handle timeout
result.onTimeout(() -> {
waitingClients.remove(user.getId());
result.setResult(ResponseEntity.ok(new EventResponse(List.of())));
});
// Handle client disconnect
result.onCompletion(() -> waitingClients.remove(user.getId()));
return result;
}
// Called by event processor (Kafka listener, etc.) when new data arrives
public void deliverEvent(String userId, Event event) {
DeferredResult<ResponseEntity<?>> result = waitingClients.remove(userId);
if (result != null) {
result.setResult(ResponseEntity.ok(new EventResponse(List.of(event))));
}
}
}The key insight: res.json() in Node.js and result.setResult() in Spring are what actually send the HTTP response and close the connection. By not calling them, the connection stays open. The response object is just a reference to an open TCP socket sitting in memory, waiting to be used.
How the Server Actually “Holds” the Connection
